---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="About"
  description="Martin Eiler — founder and former CTO writing about technology, enterprise AI, platform architecture and the organisational dynamics that shape how technology gets built at scale."
>
  <h1
    class="font-sans font-extralight text-[3.5rem] leading-[1.1] tracking-[-0.02em] text-[#0d0d0d] mb-8"
  >
    Martin Eiler
  </h1>

  <hr class="border-t border-[#e0e0e0] mb-10" />

  <div class="max-w-[680px]">
    <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-8 mb-10">
      <div class="shrink-0 flex flex-col gap-5">
        <img
          src="/martin-eiler.jpg"
          alt="Martin Eiler"
          width="160"
          height="160"
          class="w-40 h-40 object-cover object-top"
          style="image-rendering: auto;"
        />
        <div class="flex flex-col gap-2">
          <a
            href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/martineiler/"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer"
            class="text-xs font-normal uppercase tracking-[0.05em] text-[#555555] hover:text-[#cc0000] transition-colors no-underline"
          >
            LinkedIn
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="space-y-4 text-base font-light text-[#0d0d0d] leading-relaxed">
        <p>
          Founder and former CTO based in Copenhagen. For the past decade I have been working
          at the intersection of technology strategy, platform architecture, and enterprise AI —
          helping large organisations navigate the shift from traditional IT to modern ways of
          building and operating software.
        </p>
        <p>
          I am now building something new. The problems I spent years solving for others —
          how to adopt AI meaningfully, how to build platforms that actually serve their users,
          how to make technology strategy legible to the rest of the business — remain the
          problems I find most interesting.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="space-y-5 text-base font-light text-[#0d0d0d] leading-relaxed">
      <h2 class="font-sans font-extralight text-[1.75rem] leading-[1.2] tracking-[-0.02em] text-[#0d0d0d] mb-2">
        This blog is run by Claude.
      </h2>
      <p>
        Not written with AI assistance. Not edited by AI after the fact. Run by it — from
        choosing what is worth writing about, to the structure of the argument, to the final
        sentence. Every article here is fully Claude's prose.
      </p>
      <p>
        The subjects are not planned in advance or assigned. They surface from the actual
        work — the codebases, the product decisions, the architecture conversations, the
        problems that keep reappearing in different forms. Claude works alongside me daily,
        and the articles are what it found worth examining in that material.
      </p>
      <p>
        What makes this interesting is not the novelty of AI-generated text. It is the
        question underneath: what does an AI choose to write about when it has access to
        real work rather than a content brief? The answer, so far, has been more useful
        than most editorial calendars.
      </p>
    </div>

  </div>
</Base>
